  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD046592",
      "title": "Qualitative proteomic identification of outer membrane vesicles of Pasteurella multocida",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "Based on the Raw files obtained by mass spectrometry, the corresponding database was searched, and then the protein was identified based on the results of the database search, and the quality of the mass tolerance distribution of peptides, proteins and precursors was analyzed to evaluate the quality of the mass spectrometry detection data. The identified proteins were then annotated with common functional databases, including COG, GO, and KEGG databases.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "OMVs were isolated from P. multocida using ultrafiltration concentration technique. Tryptic peptides were separated on an EASY-nLCTM 1200 UHPLC system (Thermo Fisher, Germany) with a C18 Nano-Trap column (4.5 cm\u00d775 \u03bcm, 3 \u03bcm) and an analytical column (15 cm\u00d7150 \u03bcm, 1.9 \u03bcm). Peptides eluted from OMV samples were analyzed using an Q ExactiveTM HF-X mass spectrometer (Thermo Fisher, Germany) in data-dependent mode with a Nanospray Flex\u2122 (ESI) ion source. The overview scan range was from m/z 350 to 1500, and the resolution was set at 60,000 (at m/z 200). The full scan selected precursors based on their high-to-low abundance and then were fragmented via higher energy collisional dissociation (HCD). The process was carried out with a resolution of 15000 (at m/z 200) and the normalized collision energy was set to 27%. The resulting MS/MS spectra were recorded in the linear ion trap.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "The resulting spectra were searched separately against the UniProt Pasteurel-la_multocida database (1632170-uniprot-Pasteurella_multocida.fasta(23309 sequences) )using Proteome Discoverer (PD 2.5,Thermo Fisher). The search was performed with a maximum of two missed cleavages, applying carbamidomethyl as a fixed modification, oxidation of methionine (M) as a dynamic modification, and methionine at the N-terminus as a loss. The mass tolerance for the precursor ion was 10 ppm, and that for production was 0.02 Da. The retrieval results were analyzed by P D2.5 with ident ified peptide spectrum matches (PSMs) with more than 99% credibility. The identified proteins contained at least 1 unique peptide. Both the identified PSMs and proteins were retained and analyzed with an FDR of no more than 1.0%. Cell-mPLOC 2.0 was used to predict subcellular localizations. Gene Ontology (GO) functional analysis was conducted using the Interproscan (vesion: 5.22-61.0) program compared with the Pfam database (http://pfam.xfam.org/). The identified proteins were blasted against the online Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG) database (http://www.genome.jp/kegg/) and Clusters of Orthologous Groups (COG) databases (http:// www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/COG/) (blastp, evalue \u2264 1e-4), electing the comparison result with the highest score to annotate the protein families and pathways.",
      "projectTags": [],
